Analyze the following PlantUML use case model and detect if it contains any antipatterns.
Base your analysis solely on the model provided. Do not use any outside knowledge.


PlantUML Model:
@startuml
' Version 1 – contains Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

actor "Applicant" as A1
actor "Reviewer" as A2
actor "Administrator" as A3

rectangle "Scholarship Application System" {
  usecase "Register Account" as UC1
  usecase "Submit Application" as UC2
  usecase "Upload Transcript" as UC3
  usecase "Review Application" as UC4
  usecase "Award Scholarship" as UC5
  usecase "Check Application Status" as UC6
}

A1 --> UC1
A1 --> UC2
UC2 ..> UC3 : <<include>>
A1 --> UC6
A2 --> UC4
A3 --> UC5

@enduml


Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Constructs Involved: Submit Application (UC2), Upload Transcript (UC3), include relationship from UC2 to UC3
   Explanation: "Upload Transcript" (UC3) is an inclusion use case that is included by only one use case ("Submit Application" / UC2). It is not associated with any actor directly, does not include or extend any other use case, is not extended by any other use case, and is not involved in any generalization. "Upload Transcript" does not represent a complete, independently valuable service to any actor — it is merely a procedural step of submitting an application that has been improperly decomposed into a separate use case. This is a textbook instance of Functional Decomposition via the include relationship.
